UID:5ad4i39prnu82nh2efc0jo298k@google.com
CREATED:20230324T211332Z
DESCRIPTION:<span><b>Description: </b>When Alexandria's first public librar
 y was constructed just a few blocks from his home\, Samuel Wilbert Tucker\,
  a young Black attorney\, was appalled to learn that he could not use the l
 ibrary because of his race. Inspired by the legal success of the NAACP\, in
  discrimination cases\, he organized a grassroots protest to desegregate th
 e library that his tax dollars supported.</span><br><br><b><i>Public In Nam
 e Only</i></b> tells the important\, but largely forgotten\, story of Tucke
 r and a group of Black citizens who agitated for changes in the terms and c
 onditions of their lives. Employing the combined strategies of direct actio
 n\, public protest\, non-violent civil disobedience\, and municipal litigat
 ion. Tucker's initiative dovetailed with the national priorities and tactic
 s of larger civil rights organizations.<br><br>While Tucker's campaign did 
 not end with the desegregation of the Alexandria Library\, but instead resu
 lted in a "separate-and-unequal" Jim Crow Black branch. The sit-in demonstr
 ation led to a momentous early struggle for racial equity waged through civ
 il rights activism.
LAST-MODIFIED:20230324T211352Z
LOCATION:The Gum Springs Museum\, 8100 Fordson Rd\, Alexandria\, VA 22306\,
  USA
SEQUENCE:0
STATUS:CONFIRMED
SUMMARY:Book Signing and Reading With: Author Brenda Mitchell-Powell [Partn
 er Event]
TRANSP:OPAQUE
END:VEVENT
