DESCRIPTION:RSVP: <a href="https://campscui.active.com/orgs/NatureForward?e
 4q=fb3666f9-df8f-42e7-a7ce-8e3c23597538&amp\;e4p=2f196a59-9391-4d78-a920-69
 9e68939469&amp\;e4ts=1673536798&amp\;e4c=active&amp\;e4e=snlvcmpscui00001lo
 ad&amp\;e4rt=Safetynet&amp\;e4h=bd071ee9940ef3f863e5955ea92c611d#">https://
 campscui.active.com/orgs/NatureForward?e4q=fb3666f9-df8f-42e7-a7ce-8e3c2359
 7538&amp\;e4p=2f196a59-9391-4d78-a920-699e68939469&amp\;e4ts=1673536798&amp
 \;e4c=active&amp\;e4e=snlvcmpscui00001load&amp\;e4rt=Safetynet&amp\;e4h=bd0
 71ee9940ef3f863e5955ea92c611d#</a> <br><br>Description:  <span>When people 
 talk about environmental justice\, they’re often speaking about hazards suc
 h as incinerators and landfills that abut communities of color and cause th
 em harm. But environmental justice is also about decision-making systems\, 
 infrastructure investments\, and protecting culture and historical assets\,
  which communities of color will be the first to lose due to climate change
 . This talk\, by the founders of the Environmental Justice Journalism Initi
 ative\, Rona Kobell and Donzell Brown\, Jr.\, addresses all of these facets
 .</span>
